<HEAD>Restorers Will Not Remove Additions to Michelangelo Fresco</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRY LEONARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Restorers cleaning Michelangelo's ``Last
Judgment'' have decided not to remove changes another artist made
to cover images deemed offensive in the Sistine Chapel fresco,
Vatican Museum officials said.
   In 1564, Pope Pius IV, after siding with some 16th-century
church officials shocked by nude figures in the 60-by-30-foot
painting on the wall above the chapel altar, ordered artist Daniele
da Volterra to cover up the most ``indecent'' nudes.
   Fabrizio Mancinelli, directing the cleaning of Michelangelo's
Sistine Chapel frescoes, told a news conference Tuesday that
instead of painting over Michelangelo's creation, da Volterra
substituted his own fresco after first removing Michelangelo's.
   ``Since the additions are in fresco _ removing the original
fresco _ there is no real choice to take away those portions,''
said Kathleen Weil-Garris Brandt, a New York University art
historian who is a consultant on the Sistine Chapel project.
   Mancinelli and Ms. Brandt said a conference of 54 international
specialists who met last week at the Vatican decided there would be
no attempt to remove the additions.
   Michelangelo painted the ``Last Judgment'' more than 20 years
after he finished the ceiling, which he worked on between 1508 and
1512. The painting, now hidden by scaffolding, depicts a forceful
Christ standing in judgment surrounded by apprehensive saints,
angels and mythological figures.
   Mancinelli said the work to clean the masterpiece, the last
phase of the Sistine Chapel restoration, will take about four
years, including the time needed for scientific evaluation of the
painting and the cleaning methods to ensure the work is not damaged
in the process.
   The chapel restoration has been been surrounded by controversy.
   Critics led by James Beck, a Columbia University art historian,
charged that the restorters were removing some of Michelangelo's
retouchings and altering the colors of the frescoes.
   Mancinelli said the team left Michelangelo's work intact,
removing only a dirty glue-varnish that had been added by restorers
in the 17th and 18th centuries.
   To protect the newly cleaned frescoes and still allow them to be
seen by thousands of visitors each day, the Vatican is regulating
the humidity and has installed anti-dust carpets.
</TEXT>
