<HEADLINE>  A CHAPEL IN ROME JOINS A BAR IN INDIANA  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Letters to the Editor  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     As the article on the restoration of the Sistine Chapel noted, "the
restoration of Michelangelo's last piece, his apocalyptic painting of the Last
Judgment, cannot recover the true colors and painting of Michelangelo because
the 30 nudes were not just painted over, they were covered with plaster and no
one can remove the additions. They were covered up in compliance with the
rulings of the Council of Trent in 1563.";    And in the Supreme Court's
ruling against nude dancing at an Indiana bar, Chief Justice William Rehnquist
wrote for the majority that "Public nudity is the evil the state seeks to
prevent, whether or not it is combined with expressive activity." And the
nudes were covered up with the paper of a legal opinion shaped into pasties.; 
  Four hundred and 28 years have gone by, but nothing has changed. In the
minds of the modern day Republican justices, nudity is as evil as it was in
the minds of the members of the Council of Trent. In one case the decision was
the work of appointees of two Republican presidents, Reagan and Bush, in the
other, appointees of the Catholic Church.;    Morality and the power to
control it were the only issues then and are the only issues today. A legal
finding of the Supreme Court was, only, a cover up. The real issue was the
high court's power to mandate morality.;    Then, Michelangelo refused to
paint over his work. His message for the Pope was "let him make the world a
suitable place and the painting will fit in." So it was another artist who
covered the offending genitals.;    But what of today? Who shall stand for us
as Michelangelo did? Thomas Paine is no longer among us and the opposition
party has no one with the strength of character to do so. We are not yet lost,
but I fear we are close.;    -- Fred C. Stanford; Redwood City  </TEXT>
