<HEAD>Pershing II Motors to Be Destroyed in Texas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States will begin its first
destruction of nuclear missile parts under the Intermediate-range
Nuclear Forces treaty on Sept. 8.
   The Defense Department, in a brief statement Monday, said the
notice was forwarded to Moscow in accordance with the terms of the
treaty signed by President Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev in Washington last year.
   Destruction of the solid-fuel rocket motors for the Pershing II
missiles will begin on Sept. 8, ``weather permitting,'' at the
Longhorn Army Ammunition Plant near Marshall, Texas, the Pentagon
said.
   The treaty, which became effective earlier this summer, requires
the superpowers to dismantle and destroy the intermediate-and
shorter-range nuclear missiles in their arsenals. The United States
has two such types of missiles _ the ground-launched cruise missile
and the Pershing II.
</TEXT>
