<LP>
   New York -- In the fall of 1962, Robert Rauschenberg began
a series of paintings that combined silk-screened images of
photographs taken from newspapers and magazines with broadly
rendered abstract brushwork. During the next two years he
used this mixed technique for some 79 paintings, in which the
conflicting languages of photographic imagery and abstract
gestural painting are counterposed and balanced in a
remarkable way. In retrospect, these paintings seem to mark
an important point of transition between abstract
expressionism and pop art.
   Forty of these pictures are now on display at the Whitney
Museum of American art in "Robert Rauschenberg: The
Silkscreen Paintings, 1962-64," the first museum show given
to this body of work. I must admit that I went to see them
with certain misgivings. Although these pictures are
impressive when seen one at a time, their imagery tends to be
somewhat repetitious and I wondered whether a large number of
them could hold one's interest very long.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   As it turns out, the silk-screen paintings hold up very
well when seen together. Rather than being merely redundant,
the repeated use of certain images and gestures creates a
provocative thematic framework and a pictorial world that is
at once easily accessible and intensely hermetic. Because
these paintings contain depictions of familiar things and
events, they initially seem to be organized around common
experiences and shared social values. But the more you look
at them, the more ambiguous they seem, and the more they
appear to be engaged in something like a deconstruction of
social and artistic norms.
   In this, and in their stylistic and structural
ambiguities, they anticipate the aesthetics of a good deal of
postmodernist painting, from Andy Warhol to David Salle. A
lot of the strength in these pictures comes from the
continual tension they set up between public and private
experience, between the familiar image and the unexpected
context.
   On the one hand there is something reassuring about the
familiar photos of buildings, sports events, famous people
and street signs. This sense of accessibility is reinforced
by images of easily recognizable contemporary events: a space
rocket blasting off, a new pope being elected in the majestic
setting of the Sistine Chapel, Roger Maris hot on the trail
of Babe Ruth's home-run record. Even the somewhat ominous
images of helicopters and armored vehicles, signs of the
growing U.S. involvement in Southeast Asia, are balanced by
pictures of the Statue of Liberty, American eagles,
flag-bedecked Boy Scout parades, and astronauts floating in
space.
   The early '60s were the best of times and the worst of
times, these images seem to suggest. But the elaborate
brushwork reminds you that these are not merely photo
montages, but paintings, and very expressively executed ones
at that. The Whitney's installation brings out the formal
richness of these pictures very nicely. It devotes the first
galleries exclusively to works in black and white. This not
only follows Mr. Rauschenberg's own progression from black
and white to color when he was making the pictures, but also
points up the stronger documentary emphasis of the monochrome
works.
   Later, when Mr. Rauschenberg begins to work with bold
swatches of bright color, his compositions become more
flamboyantly expressionistic. Throughout, the brushstrokes
seem to assert the artist's physical presence and to act as a
strong mediating force between the diverse events represented
in the silk-screen photos. This counterpoint between the
coolly objective and the intensely personal heightens our
consciousness of our own dual awareness of the world. Like
the artist, we find ourselves marveling at how many different
things there are going on all at once, with us right in the
middle of them all.
   Art with a capital "A" plays an important if ambiguous
role in many of these pictures. Images of Velazquez's svelte
"Rokeby Venus" keep popping up, along with parts of Rubens's
"Toilet of Venus," suggesting that maybe art and the subjects
of art are as much part of everyday life as street signs or
baseball players. Reinforcing these overt allusions to works
of art are numerous indirect references, some of them fraught
with subtle irony.
   In "Bait" (1963), an image of the Sistine Chapel
containing Michelangelo's scenes from Genesis is superimposed
on a photo of a construction site. In "Express" (1963), a
multiple-exposure photograph of a nude woman walking down an
incline evokes Marcel Duchamp's "Nude Descending a
Staircase." The paintings are also full of formal puns, the
painterly equivalents of wordplay. At the top of "Choke"
(1964), for example, a burst of dripping orange paint
cascades down against a "One Way" street sign that
insistently points in the opposite direction.
   Mr. Rauschenberg has sometimes been characterized as a
passive observer of the world around him, a man without ideas
guided purely by his intuition. This exhibition, I think,
gives the lie to that myth. When he made these paintings, Mr.
Rauschenberg seems to have been as involved in intellectual
sleight of hand as he was with manual dexterity. He was also
both clever and courageous enough to know when to stop. In
1964, after he had won the grand prize for painting at the
Venice Biennale, he telephoned a friend in New York and asked
that the more than 100 silk-screens he had used for these
paintings be destroyed, so that he could start with fresh
imagery when he got back. The exhibition, which is
accompanied by a fully illustrated catalog, will be on view
until March 17 and will not travel.
