<LEADPARA>  City officials brought the most talented graffiti artists in Los Angeles to a
Hollywood studio last month for a demonstration they hoped would gain
community backing for a program to encourage spray-can Picassos.;   The city
cultural affairs department had hoped to prove to civic leaders and
community-based graffiti abatement programs that graffiti art can be
beautiful, and that a youth program to support the craft could help steer
teen-agers away from crime and drugs.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  California News  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  BID TO FIND SPRAY-CAN ART HITS WALL OF OPPOSITION  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     But as the Raleigh Studios sound stage filled with paint fumes, and 1,000
youthful graffiti fans cheered on their favorite artists, a handful of avowed
graffiti fighters in the audience saw that -- to their horror -- the city
actually was contemplating funding a program to help their enemies.;   "I
think it's wrong, absolutely wrong," said Hannah Dyke, president and
co-founder of Sylmar Graffiti Busters. Sylmar is an area of Los Angeles.;  
"To me, that would do nothing more than perpetuate the problem," Dyke said.
"Every artist who came to see it also added their 'tagging' in the area.;  
"The entire area for miles around ended up becoming a tagging trail of who
came to see the artwork.";   City officials acknowledge it will be a battle to
win approval for a graffiti-art program because it touches on such sensitive
issues as cultural and generational differences, the question of property
rights vs. freedom of expression, and the connection between graffiti and gang
violence.;   "One of the things we've been saying to all of the anti-graffiti
folks is that their approach has got to be a little bit more holistic," said
Al Nodal, general manager of the cultural affairs department.;   "A few years
ago, we thought all we would have to do is give everybody some beige paint and
we would get rid of graffiti," Nodal said. "To be smart about graffiti, we
can't just say it's all bad.;   "We need to identify the parts that are bad
and get rid of that, and identify those parts that are good and try to help
some kids out.";   The concept of encouraging good street art and providing
sites for it to take place legally is one that many members of the city's
artistic community support.;   The artists say graffiti can be art without
being vandalism.;   "We all dislike tagging and vandalism," said Diane
Alexander, a Los Angeles fiction writer who founded a street art support group
called the Graffiti Coalition. "But all they do is try to arrest the guys or
buff out what's on the wall -- the tagging. It's not working. The tagging is
exploding.;   "So I think that it's more than time that we tried an
alternative.";   Some Los Angeles homeowners say any attempt to glorify
graffiti as art threatens their neighborhoods. Graffiti, no matter how well
painted, is vandalism by definition, they said.;   "If Michelangelo had broken
into the Sistine Chapel and sprayed the ceiling, that's graffiti, that's not
art," said Gerald A. Silver, president of Homeowners of Encino.;   Graffiti
has developed from the turf marking and public threats of the street gangs, to
the tagging of rebellious youth, to "piecing," in which crews of spray-can
painters "throw up" their masterpieces on the wall.  </TEXT>
