<TEXT>  (box) THE GIRL FROM MARS:; 8 p.m. Saturday, Family Channel (cable); (box) A
SEASON OF GIANTS: Part 1, 5 and 7 p.m.; Sunday; Part 2, 5 and 7 p.m. Monday,
TNT (cable);  A RARELY seen version of Sherlock Holmes' most popular
adventure, starring TV's "Dr. Who" as the famed sleuth; an original family
film about an alienated high school girl who just might be an alien; and an
epic miniseries about Michelangelo, Raphael and Leonardo from the man who gave
us "Shogun" -- they're all part of a TV weekend devoted to the unusual.;   
Holmes hounds, enjoy;  First up -- and easiest to take -- is "The Hound of the
Baskervilles," which San Jose's KTEH (Ch. 54) has dusted off to replace its
usual "Mystery Night" lineup as a special event for the station's pledge
period.;    This handsome edition of Conan Doyle's "Hound," filmed on the
story's actual Dartmoor locations, isn't new, but hardly anyone else shows it
these days. So it may seem like a discovery to fans of the station's "Dr. Who"
serial who've never seen its star, Tom Baker, play anything else. Baker's
Holmes is excellent.;    There's a good reason why "Hound" has been filmed so
often: It has everything -- gloomy moors, a quicksand "mire," an escaped
convict, a fake Holmes, a mystery man, an eccentric recluse, whispered
warnings and, of course, the savage "hound of hell"!;    Divided into four
half-hour episodes, this "Hound" is less frightening than interesting, but it
does give Dr. Watson (Terence Rigby) one of his toughest solo assignments, and
it offers Holmes a chance to fool everybody -- including us.;    Strictly from
Mars;  In contrast, the only people fooled by the Family Channel's "The Girl
from Mars" were the people who put up the money to make this well-intentioned
but stupid cable movie.;    At first, it seemed like an interesting concept: A
bookish, unpopular high school girl (Sarah Sawatsky) is so traumatized by the
death of her mother that she escapes into a favorite fantasy and actually
begins to believe she's from Mars.;    The program also offers a rare
opportunity to watch veteran actor Eddie Albert, who plays a kooky scientist,
working alongside his real-life son, Edward Albert, who plays the girl's
widowed father. But the story veers off in an infantile direction and leaves
them both looking rather embarrassed.;    What might have been an interesting
commentary on an alienated youngster turns increasingly silly with each new
"special power" young DeeDee (Sawatsky) reveals. By the time the troubled girl
shaves her head to make it easier "to peel off my skin," all poignancy is
plundered.;    Maybe kids will enjoy this -- mutant kids, that is, with
dehydrated taste buds.;    Spaghetti 'Lives of the Artists';  Quite another
story is TNT's two-part spectacle of late 15th-century Italy, "A Season of
Giants." This miniseries is sort of the All-Star Game for Renaissance artists
or, if you prefer, a spaghetti remake of "The Agony and the Ecstasy" with a
little Leonardo on the side.;    Like most Italian-made TV shows, this one
looks great but sounds as if it were recorded in the BART tube by drunken
language students.;    Still, it has many effective moments, especially the
one in which Leonardo da Vinci gets ticked off at the pretty girl modeling for
his "Mona Lisa" because she moves just when he's getting the smile right. "A
few moments ago, she was truly beautiful," he fumes. "Now that moment has
fled.";    The miniseries, directed by American Jerry London, who made
"Shogun," is about the rise to fame of Michelangelo (Mark Frankel) in a time
of perhaps the greatest artistic ferment the world has ever witnessed. His
rivalry with Leonardo (John Glover) and his influence on the young Raphael
(Andrea Prodan) are examined. And the final part of the film deals with
Michelangelo's testy relationship with Pope Julius II (F. Murray Abraham), who
forces him to tackle his greatest achievement, the Sistine ceiling.;    I'm
sorry to say this is all rather hard to follow, and the drama ends abruptly
with a peculiar sequence suggesting Michelangelo did it all to win the respect
of his highly critical father.;    Yet "A Season of Giants" is very impressive
when it shows us "behind the scenes" glimpses of the making of great art, such
as Michelangelo's creation of his towering "David.";    There's precious
little action, though, and what romance there is comes off as gratuitous,
especially the scene where the glamorous Onoria (Ornella Muti) shows her
breasts to Michelangelo as "a gift" for his genius.;    The miniseries
presents Michelangelo as rather mean-spirited. However, he meets his match in
Pope Julius, who wants to "fill his papacy with the din of deeds" and refuses
to let Michelangelo back out of the job that will take the rest of his life.; 
  Young Mark Frankel, the British newcomer who made such a vivid impression as
the lover of Catherine the Great in TNT's "Young Catherine," is a superb
Michelangelo. Glover's Leonardo is a nice change of pace for the actor who
usually plays heels, villains or losers. Abraham, the Oscar-winner for
"Amadeus," is excellent in a role that seems too brief.;    But, even though
"A Season of Giants" has many merits, it's still like a long train ride: It
may take you where you want to go, but you'll have to guard against falling
asleep along the way.  </TEXT>
